{{Ada/Navigation|Attributes|'Pos}}
__TOC__

== Description ==

The 'Pos attribute is defined for all discrete types. It is a function returning the argument's position number as a universal_integer; the prefix S must be a subtype name.
(Universal integers are implicitly converted to any specific integer type as required by the context.)

 {{Ada/kw|function}} S'Pos (Arg: S'Base) {{Ada/kw|return}} ''universal_integer'';

For enumeration types, position numbers start at 0; if the argument does not denote a valid value (perhaps because of an uninitialized 
variable), the exception Program_Error is raised.
For integer types, the attribute returns the value converted to universal_integer. Note that the actual argument need not belong to the subtype S.

Note that representation clauses do not affect position numbering. Whatever underlying value the enumerated value has, the position number will remain the same.

== Example ==

 I: Integer := -30;

 {{Ada/pragma|Assert}} (Integer'Pos(I) = -30);  {{Ada/--|of type universal_integer}}

 {{Ada/kw|type}} My_Enum {{Ada/kw|is}}  (Enum1, Enum2, Enum3);
 {{Ada/kw|for}}  My_Enum {{Ada/kw|use}} (Enum1 => 2, Enum2 => 4, Enum3 => 6);
 ...
 {{Ada/pragma|Assert}} (My_Enum'Pos(Enum1) = 2);  {{Ada/--|Wrong}}
 {{Ada/pragma|Assert}} (My_Enum'Pos(Enum1) = 0);  {{Ada/--|Right}}
 {{Ada/pragma|Assert}} (My_Enum'Pos(Enum3) = 2);

 {{Ada/kw|subtype}} My_Enum_Sub {{Ada/kw|is}} My_Enum {{Ada/kw|range}} Enum1 .. Enum2;

 {{Ada/pragma|Assert}} (My_Enum_Sub'Pos (Enum3) = 2);  {{Ada/--|Enum3 does not belong to My_Enum_Sub}}

== See also ==

The inverse of the 'Pos attribut is [[Ada Programming/Attributes/'Val|'Val]].

For a detailed explanation of universal_integer, see [[Ada Programming/Type System|Type System]]: Elaborated Discussion of Types for Signed Integer Types.
