{{Ada/Navigation|Attributes|'Bit_Order}}
__TOC__

== Description ==

R<b>'Bit_Order</b> is a [[:Category:Ada Programming/Representation attributes|representation attribute]] used to specify the [[w:bit numbering|bit numbering]] of a [[Ada Programming/Representation clauses|record representation clause]] (for a record type). The bit ordering is of type <tt>{{Ada/package|System}}.Bit_Order</tt>, and may be either:
* <tt>High_Order_First</tt> when the bit 0 is the [[w:most significant bit|most significant bit]]
* <tt>Low_Order_First</tt> when the bit 0 is the [[w:least significant bit|least significant bit]]
The constant <tt>{{Ada/package|System}}.Default_Bit_Order</tt> represents the native bit numbering of the platform.

It is worth noting that the bit ordering only affects the bit numbering for a record representation clause, and ''not the [[w:endianness|byte order]]'' of its (multibyte) fields.<ref>
Note that when the ARM talks about "big endian" and "litte endian" in the definition of the 'Bit_Order attribute it really means ''bit endianness'', not ''byte endianness''. (Nowadays the term ''endianness'' is usually reserved for talking about [[w:endianness|byte order]], although it can also be used for [[w:bit numbering|bit numbering]].) Thus, in this context, when the ARM says "little endian" it refers to "[[w:LSB0|LSB 0]]", and when it says "big endian" this is the same as "[[w:MSB0|MSB 0]]": <blockquote>«''<tt>High_Order_First</tt> (known in the vernacular as “big endian”) means that the first bit of a storage element (bit 0) is the most significant bit (interpreting the sequence of bits that represent a component as an unsigned integer value). <tt>Low_Order_First</tt> (known in the vernacular as “little endian”) means the opposite: the first bit is the least significant.''» {{Ada/Ref RM|13|5|3|par=2|id=I4589}}<blockquote></ref>

== Example ==

The following two sets of representation clauses specify the same register layout in any machine / compiler:

 {{Ada/kw|type}} Device_Register {{Ada/kw|is}}
     {{Ada/kw|record}}
        Ready : Status_Flag;
        Error : Error_Flag;
        Data  : Unsigned_16;
     {{Ada/kw|end}} {{Ada/kw|record}};

 {{Ada/kw|for}}  Device_Register {{Ada/kw|use}}
     {{Ada/kw|record}}
        Ready {{Ada/kw|at}} 0 {{Ada/kw|range}}  0 .. 0;
        Error {{Ada/kw|at}} 0 {{Ada/kw|range}}  1 .. 1;
        {{Ada/--|Reserved bits}}
        Data  {{Ada/kw|at}} 0 {{Ada/kw|range}} 16 .. 31;
     {{Ada/kw|end}} {{Ada/kw|record}};
 {{Ada/kw|for}} Device_Register'Size      {{Ada/kw|use}} 32;
 '''{{Ada/kw|for}} Device_Register'Bit_Order {{Ada/kw|use}} System.Low_Order_First;'''

 {{Ada/pragma|Atomic}} (Device_Register);

If the bit order is modified, the bit numbering of all the elements of the record representation clause must be reversed:

 {{Ada/kw|type}} Device_Register {{Ada/kw|is}}
     {{Ada/kw|record}}
        Ready : Status_Flag;
        Error : Error_Flag;
        Data  : Unsigned_16;
     {{Ada/kw|end}} {{Ada/kw|record}};

 {{Ada/kw|for}}  Device_Register {{Ada/kw|use}}
     {{Ada/kw|record}}
        Ready {{Ada/kw|at}} 0 {{Ada/kw|range}} 31 .. 31;   {{Ada/--|Bit numbering has changed}}
        Error {{Ada/kw|at}} 0 {{Ada/kw|range}} 30 .. 30;   {{Ada/--|Bit numbering has changed}}
        {{Ada/--|Reserved bits}}
        Data  {{Ada/kw|at}} 0 {{Ada/kw|range}}  0 .. 15;   {{Ada/--|Bit numbering has changed (but byte order is not affected)}}
     {{Ada/kw|end}} {{Ada/kw|record}};
 {{Ada/kw|for}} Device_Register'Size      {{Ada/kw|use}} 32;
 '''{{Ada/kw|for}} Device_Register'Bit_Order {{Ada/kw|use}} System.High_Order_First;''' {{Ada/--|Reverse bit order}}

 {{Ada/pragma|Atomic}} (Device_Register);

Both can be interchangeably used in the same machine. But note that in two machines with different endianness the <tt>Data</tt> field will have the native ''byte order'' regardless of the ''bit order'' specified in the representation clauses.

== Incorrect usage ==

{{:Ada Programming/Attributes/'Bit_Order:3}}

== Portability ==

=== Ada versions ===

{{Ada/2005/Incompatibility}}

* Available in Ada&nbsp;95 and Ada&nbsp;2005.

=== Compilers ===

'Bit_Order is a portability aid between different compilers. In Ada&nbsp;83 the bit numbering in representation clauses was implementation dependent so compilers can choose for each platform its natural ordering.<ref>{{Ada/83/Cite RM|13|4|
 |      title = Record Representation Clauses
 | accessdate = 2008-12-20
 |      quote = The range defines the bit positions of the storage place, relative to the storage unit. The first storage unit of a record is numbered zero. The first bit of a storage unit is numbered zero. The ordering of bits in a storage unit is machine_dependent and may extend to adjacent storage units.
}}</ref> However, this introduced portability problems between compilers.

It is a standard attribute since Ada&nbsp;95, so it must be accepted by all Ada&nbsp;95 and Ada&nbsp;2005 compilers. Compilers are suggested (but not required) to support the non-default bit order. [[Ada Programming/GNAT|GNAT]] supports both bit numberings, but recent versions give a warning if the non-default order is specified.

=== Platforms ===

Although this attribute can be a portability aid between different platforms, the byte order of some (multibyte) fields will not probably be the same in machines with a different endianness.

For example, explicit use of 'Bit_Order will probably enhance portability of [[w:device driver|device driver]]s, but in general it is useless for [[w:computer network programming|network programming]] or for portable [[w:file format|file format]]s.

== Interfacing ==

Record representation clauses are a unique feature of the Ada language as far as the authors know, so there is no need to have a feature similar to attribute 'Bit_Order in other programming languages. It is common practice in other programming languages to use masks and bit operations explicitly, thus the native bit numbering must always be used.

